{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638133","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638133"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:50:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:50:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17693"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17693","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17693"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10407"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72077"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10407"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17693"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57547"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"10453"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24318"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24351"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72077"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EInner hair cells within the organ of Corti are essential for hearing.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of inner hair cells in the cochlea?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Amplify incoming sound waves","Support outer hair cells","Filter background noise","Produce endolymph fluid","Convert sound waves into electrical signals"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of inner hair cells is to \u003Cstrong\u003Econvert sound waves into electrical signals\u003C/strong\u003E through mechanotransduction. When sound waves cause movement of the basilar membrane, the stereocilia of inner hair cells are deflected, opening mechanically-gated ion channels. This leads to depolarisation and release of glutamate onto afferent auditory nerve fibres.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmplify incoming sound waves\u003C/strong\u003E - This function belongs to outer hair cells, which enhance cochlear sensitivity through their electromotile properties.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupport outer hair cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Supporting cells known as Deiters\u0027 cells provide the structural support to hair cells, not inner hair cells.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFilter background noise\u003C/strong\u003E - While noise filtering occurs in hearing, this is achieved through neural processing in the central auditory pathways rather than at the hair cell level.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduce endolymph fluid\u003C/strong\u003E - The stria vascularis is responsible for endolymph production and maintenance, not inner hair cells.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInner hair cells are the true sensory receptors of the auditory system, converting mechanical energy from sound waves into electrical signals that can be processed by the brain.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Inner hair cells are the primary sensory receptors in the cochlea that convert sound waves into neural signals.","Inner hair cells release glutamate as their neurotransmitter to activate afferent auditory nerve fibres.","Stereocilia deflection opens mechanically-gated ion channels, leading to depolarisation of inner hair cells."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57547"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17693"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57547","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57547"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T22:15:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T22:20:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10407"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72077"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4942"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":[],"description":null